## 2. The Mathematical Event: From Collapse to Coordination

The GNST, named and defined in Paper 1 (§3.3, §6), states that every self-adjoint operator A on H, when its domain is restricted to Φ, has a complete set of generalized eigenvectors in Φ′. Any state ψ ∈ H admits the expansion:

> **ψ = ∫ ⟨eλ, ψ⟩ eλ dμ(λ)**

where eλ ∈ Φ′ are distributional [[Appendix I - Dictionary of Terms#Eigenstate|eigenstate]]s, ⟨eλ, ψ⟩ is the duality pairing, and dμ(λ) is the spectral measure on the spectrum of A.

The structural significance of this theorem for the present paper lies in what each component is.

**ψ ∈ H** is a state in H — the domain of all structured, well-defined quantum states. It carries amplitude, phase, and the complete probability structure of whatever it describes.

**eλ ∈ Φ′** are distributional eigenstates drawn from Φ′, the distributional dual. The canonical example is the position eigenstate: eλ = δ(x − x₀), a Dirac delta — pure localization at a point, infinite intensity, zero spread. It is not a structured state. It cannot be normalized as an element of H. It is pure potential — the limiting case of localization that Φ′ contains and H cannot.

**dμ(λ)** is the spectral measure. It is the coordinative mechanism — the mathematical object that converts the distributional potential of Φ′ and the structured amplitude of H into a definite, located, measurable outcome.

**⟨eλ, ψ⟩** is the inner product extended across the duality pairing: the overlap measured between an H-state and a Φ′-eigenstate.

The collapse is the event in which this expansion produces a specific outcome λ₀. Before the collapse: ψ is a superposition distributed across the full spectral range. Φ′ contains all possible localizations as distributional eigenstates. After the collapse: λ₀ is definite. A specific position, a specific energy, a specific time — a point in spacetime has been created.

This is not a metaphor. The Dirac delta δ(x − x₀) is a mathematical object in Φ′. The spectral measure selects x₀. That selection is the creation of a location. The sequence of such selections is the creation of time. Space and time are not containers that pre-exist events; they are constituted by the sequence of collapse events, each one drawing a definite outcome from the infinite distributional potential of Φ′ through the structured amplitude of H.

**The result that is coordinated.** A single collapse yields a single outcome; creation is not a single outcome but the whole manifold of them, held together as one coherent, convergent order. What makes that manifold cohere — what determines which outcomes are adjacent, which sequences converge, which limits exist — is the nuclear topology τ_nuclear (Paper 1). The collapse events produce the actualizations; the nuclear topology integrates them into a single realized space. This is creation read from the result side: *coordinative actualization* — the ongoing actualization of collapse-events, coordinated into one coherent creation. The event is the subject of Paper 1; its integration is the subject of this paper.

**What the scientist is looking at.** Stated without the framework's vocabulary, the section above is the *measurement problem.* A quantum system is a superposition — a distribution over possibilities — until something makes one outcome definite; the passage from the spread to the single result is the event physics has never derived from the unitary dynamics alone, and the one its interpretations divide over. The spectral collapse above is that event, named structurally: the GNST drawing one eigenstate eλ ∈ Φ′ from the distribution. Read this way, two features the physicist will recognize fall out. *Why definite outcomes in a particular basis, rather than arbitrary superpositions* — the spectral measure dμ singles out a basis, which is the structural form of what decoherence calls einselection, the environment-induced selection of stable pointer states: outcomes are drawn in the eigenbasis of the operating structure. And *why the separate outcomes agree* — the collapses do not each open a private world; they are coordinated into one consistent record, a single quasi-classical history in which every observer's results fit together, and the structure that coordinates them is the nuclear topology τ_nuclear. The measurement problem, the preferred-basis problem, and the consistency of the classical world are, read here, three questions about one coordination. *(Offered as the framework's structural reading of these problems, in the physicist's own terms — a recognition of the territory, not a claim to have closed debates the field keeps open.)*

